{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01PuosURHvBGiaapfG5RWU47","type":"tool_result","content":"  1280→\n  1281→### CRITICAL: Recurring state corruption — ralph state reconciliation overwrites committed `done` statuses\n  1282→\n  1283→**Occurrences:** Sessions 6, 7, 8, 9, and now 10 (five consecutive sessions).\n  1284→\n  1285→**Root cause:** Story 11-3 (`state-reconciliation-on-session-start`) implements reconciliation logic that runs when ralph starts a new session. This logic re-derives story status from incomplete heuristics (e.g., checking whether a proof document exists at a specific path, or whether acResults are populated in the JSON). When these heuristics fail to detect a story as `done`, reconciliation overwrites the committed `done` status back to an earlier state like `review`.\n  1286→\n  1287→**Why it keeps happening:**\n  1288→1. Many stories marked `done` via manual `state set` or direct JSON edits do not have `proofPath` or `acResults` populated — reconciliation sees them as incomplete.\n  1289→2. The reconciliation logic does not treat `done` as a terminal state that should never regress.\n  1290→3. Each session, the operator must manually re-fix the same stories, and new stories completed in that session become vulnerable to the same regression in the next session.\n  1291→\n  1292→**Impact:**\n  1293→- Every session starts with 2-5 minutes of state repair instead of productive work.\n  1294→- Sprint progress numbers are unreliable without manual verification.\n  1295→- The sprint counter in `sprint-state.json` shows `\"done\": 70` despite all 74 stories being `done` in sprint-status.yaml — the counter itself is stale.\n  1296→\n  1297→### State counter drift\n  1298→\n  1299→`sprint-state.json` reports `\"done\": 70` but sprint-status.yaml shows 74/74 stories done and 17/17 epics done. Epic-14 shows `storiesDone: 4` (should be 7) and epic-16 shows `storiesDone: 7` (should be 8). The aggregate counter and per-epic counters are not being recalculated when individual story statuses are repaired.\n  1300→\n  1301→## 3. Cost Analysis\n  1302→\n  1303→**Cumulative project costs** (all epics, all sessions):\n  1304→\n  1305→| Metric | Value |\n  1306→|--------|-------|\n  1307→| Total API-equivalent cost | $622.44 |\n  1308→| Total API calls | 4,621 |\n  1309→| Average cost per story | $3.34 (152 story-phases tracked) |\n  1310→\n  1311→**Delta from session 9:** +$66.38 (+523 API calls). This delta covers session 9 work (story 16-8 full lifecycle) plus session 10 overhead.\n  1312→\n  1313→**Token breakdown:**\n  1314→- Cache reads: $386.58 (62%) — dominant cost, expected for long-context sessions\n  1315→- Cache writes: $139.85 (22%)\n  1316→- Output: $95.84 (15%)\n  1317→- Input: $0.17 (0%)\n  1318→\n  1319→**Phase breakdown:**\n  1320→- Verification: $349.71 (56.2%) — remains the most expensive phase\n  1321→- Orchestrator: $110.89 (17.8%)\n  1322→- Retro: $60.48 (9.7%)\n  1323→- Create-story: $36.58 (5.9%)\n  1324→- Code-review: $34.70 (5.6%)\n  1325→- Dev-story: $30.07 (4.8%)\n  1326→\n  1327→**Session 10 cost:** Near-zero. Only cost was this retrospective session itself — no subagents, no builds, no verification.\n  1328→\n  1329→## 4. What Went Well"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01XQb88j2XyoAEyWba8pEnv2","session_id":"9a32080c-76ef-409a-9a0e-138b5be12a95","uuid":"0b354a0e-1347-472a-8436-212774419e5a","timestamp":"2026-03-27T14:17:54.606Z"}
